3. What technologies power the “thinking” layer of modern AI agents?
    Large Language Models (LLMs): For understanding and generating language, chain-of-thought reasoning.
    Machine Learning/Deep Learning: For pattern recognition (e.g., in vision sensors) and reinforcement learning.
    Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG): To pull in relevant, up-to-date information from external knowledge sources.
    Traditional Programming & Logic: For “if-then-else” rules, task planning, and decomposition.
-------
4. Can you give a concrete example of how an AI agent works?
    Yes, a travel booking agent is a good example:
    
    Sense: You input your travel dates and destination via text (chatbot) or it reads your calendar.
    Think:
    It consults its knowledge base for your preferences (favorite airlines, hotel chains, desire for a running route), real-time data (flight prices, hotel availability), and company policy (travel budget caps, preferred vendors).
    Its reasoning engine processes all this to find the optimal itinerary that meets all criteria.
    Act: It autonomously books the flights and hotels by interacting with reservation system APIs and provides you with e-tickets.
    Feedback: It asks for your rating on the trip or automatically checks if the booking was successful, using that information to improve future recommendations.
